        Conclusions
        Nontypeable 
        Haemophilus influenzae forms biofilms
        in vitro. Clinical isolates show substantial variability in
        their ability to grow as biofilms. <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">Three</NUMEX> major outer
        membrane <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">proteins</ENAMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">P2</TIMEX>, <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">P5 and P6</TIMEX>, are expressed during
        growth as a biofilm. Expression of an epitope on
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">lipooligosaccharide</ENAMEX> is altered during growth as a biofilm.
        Pili are important in <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">biofilm</ENAMEX> formation. As the role of
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">biofilms</ENAMEX> in human infection becomes better defined,
        characterization of biofilms may be important in
        understanding the pathogenesis of infection and immune
        response to nontypeable 
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">H.</ENAMEX> influenzae in <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">children</ENAMEX> with otitis
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">media</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">adults</ENAMEX> with <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">COPD</ENAMEX>.
      
      
